.TH NETLOOM-CLEARPASS 7 "March 2026" "netloom 1.9.11" "Miscellaneous Information Manual"
.SH NAME
netloom-clearpass \- ClearPass plugin reference for netloom.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.EX
netloom load clearpass
netloom server use <profile>
netloom cache update
netloom <module> <service> <action> [options]
.EE

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B netloom-clearpass
documents the bundled ClearPass plugin for
.BR netloom (1).

The plugin targets HPE Aruba ClearPass Policy Manager and discovers the API
surface dynamically from the documentation endpoints exposed by the selected
server. Because of that, available modules, services, actions, request fields,
and response metadata can vary between deployments and software versions.

Use this manual for the ClearPass-specific behavior that does not belong in the
shared
.BR netloom (1)
manual: configuration layout, authentication methods, discovery workflow,
privilege-aware catalog behavior, filtering conventions, and the
profile-to-profile
.B copy
and
.B diff
workflows.

.SH CONFIGURATION
The ClearPass plugin stores configuration under:

.PP
.EX
~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/
.EE

Important files and directories:

.TP
.B defaults.env
Plugin-wide defaults such as the active profile, TLS verification, timeout, and
path overrides.

.TP
.B profiles/<profile>.env
Per-profile connection settings such as
.BR NETLOOM_SERVER .

.TP
.B credentials/<profile>.env
Per-profile authentication settings such as
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_ID ,
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF ,
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET ,
.BR NETLOOM_API_TOKEN ,
or
.BR NETLOOM_API_TOKEN_FILE .

A typical layout looks like:

.PP
.EX
~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/defaults.env
~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/profiles/dev.env
~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/credentials/dev.env
.EE

Minimal profile connection settings:

.PP
.EX
NETLOOM_SERVER=clearpass.example.com:443
.EE

Minimal OAuth client credentials:

.PP
.EX
NETLOOM_CLIENT_ID=dev-client-id
NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF=dev/client-secret
.EE

Direct
.B NETLOOM_*
environment variables still override profile files when set in the current
shell session.

.SH AUTHENTICATION
The ClearPass plugin supports three practical authentication paths.

.TP
.B OAuth client credentials
Uses
.BR NETLOOM_SERVER ,
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_ID ,
and either
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF
or
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET .

.TP
.B Direct bearer token
Uses
.BR NETLOOM_API_TOKEN .

.TP
.B Token file
Uses
.BR NETLOOM_API_TOKEN_FILE .
The file may contain either a raw token or JSON with an
.B access_token
field.

When a login secret is needed, the runtime checks in this order:
.RS
.IP "1." 4
.B NETLOOM_API_TOKEN
.IP "2." 4
.B NETLOOM_API_TOKEN_FILE
.IP "3." 4
keychain-resolved
.B NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF
.IP "4." 4
plaintext
.B NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET
.RE

.SH KEYCHAIN SETUP
When
.B NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF
is configured, the runtime resolves the client secret from the OS keychain with:
.RS
.TP
.B service
netloom/clearpass
.TP
.B username
the literal value of
.BR NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF .
.RE

Typical setup:

.PP
.EX
python -m keyring set netloom/clearpass dev/client-secret
.EE

.PP
.EX
NETLOOM_CLIENT_ID=dev-client-id
NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF=dev/client-secret
.EE

To inspect the backend that Python
.B keyring
sees:

.PP
.EX
python -m keyring diagnose
python -m keyring --help
.EE

To verify a stored secret:

.PP
.EX
python -m keyring get netloom/clearpass dev/client-secret
.EE

In headless Linux or WSL-style environments, a keyring backend may need to be
installed and unlocked explicitly. One workable pattern is:

.PP
.EX
sudo apt install -y gnome-keyring
dbus-run-session -- bash
echo 'choose-a-keyring-password' | gnome-keyring-daemon --unlock
python -m keyring set netloom/clearpass dev/client-secret
.EE

If
.B NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET_REF
is configured but no usable backend exists, the runtime only falls back to
plaintext
.B NETLOOM_CLIENT_SECRET
when that plaintext value is also configured.

.SH DISCOVERY AND CACHE
The ClearPass plugin discovers API structure from documentation endpoints such
as:

.TP
.B /api-docs
Top-level module and service discovery.

.TP
.B /api/apigility/documentation/<Module-v1>
Action metadata, request field hints, and endpoint details for a module.

Refresh discovery metadata when the ClearPass server is upgraded, when API
features change, or when help/completion looks stale:

.PP
.EX
netloom cache clear
netloom cache update
.EE

The resulting cache powers shell completion, context-aware help, and command
validation.

.SH PRIVILEGE-AWARE CATALOG
During
.B netloom cache update
the ClearPass plugin also queries:

.TP
.B /api/oauth/privileges
Effective runtime privileges for the authenticated API client.

The plugin keeps the full discovered catalog, then builds a stricter default
visible view from verified privilege mappings. This makes normal help,
completion, and command discovery better match what the current API client can
actually access.

Normal CLI behavior uses the visible catalog. To troubleshoot or inspect the
retained full discovery data, use:

.PP
.EX
netloom --catalog-view=full ?
netloom --catalog-view=full <module> <service> ?
netloom --catalog-view=full <module> <service> <action> ?
.EE

.SH FILTERING
When an endpoint supports server-side filtering, the ClearPass plugin accepts
either shorthand filters or full JSON expressions.

Shorthand examples:

.PP
.EX
--filter=name:equals:TEST
--filter=name:contains:guest
--filter=id:in:1,2,3
--filter=enabled:exists:true
.EE

Supported shorthand operators:

.PP
.EX
equals
not-equals
contains
in
not-in
gt
gte
lt
lte
exists
.EE

Useful JSON patterns include:

.PP
.EX
{"key":{"$eq":"value"}}
{"key":{"$contains":"value"}}
{"key":{"$in":["value1","value2"]}}
{"$and":[filter1,filter2]}
{"$or":[filter1,filter2]}
{"$not":{filter}}
.EE

Advanced JSON examples:

.PP
.EX
--filter='{"name":{"$contains":"TEST"}}'
--filter='{"$and":[{"name":{"$contains":"TEST"}},{"status":{"$eq":"Known"}}]}'
.EE

Shell quoting matters because JSON expressions are passed as strings.

.SH COMMON OPTIONS
The following common CLI options are especially relevant when working with the
ClearPass plugin:

.TP
.BI --file= PATH
Path to JSON/CSV bulk payload input.

.TP
.BI --out= PATH
Override the output file path.

.TP
.BI --data-format= JSON|CSV|RAW
Output format (default:
.BR json ).

.TP
.BI --csv-fieldnames= A,B,C
Fields and order for CSV output.

.TP
.BI --filter= JSON|FIELD:OP:VALUE
Server-side filter applied across all matching pages.

.TP
.BI --limit= N
Page size for list/get
.B --all
and
.B copy
requests.

.TP
.BI --calculate-count= true|false
Request total count metadata.

.TP
.BI --log-level= LEVEL
Select log level (default:
.BR info ).

.TP
.BI --api-token= TOKEN
Use an existing bearer token.

.TP
.BI --token-file= PATH
Load a bearer token from a file.

.TP
.BI --encrypt= enable|disable
Mask or show secret fields.

.SH COPY WORKFLOW
The ClearPass plugin supports copying resources between named profiles without
manual export and replay steps.

Preferred syntax:

.PP
.EX
netloom <module> <service> copy --from=SOURCE --to=TARGET [options]
.EE

Useful options include:

.TP
.B --dry-run
Preview planned writes without changing the target profile.

.TP
.BI --match-by= auto|name|id
Choose how target objects are matched.

.TP
.BI --on-conflict= fail|skip|update|replace
Choose the write strategy when a match already exists.

.TP
.BI --save-source= FILE
Save fetched source objects. If omitted, a generated file under
.B NETLOOM_OUT_DIR
is still written.

.TP
.BI --save-payload= FILE
Save normalized write payloads. If omitted, a generated file under
.B NETLOOM_OUT_DIR
is still written.

.TP
.BI --save-plan= FILE
Save the planned operations. If omitted, a generated file under
.B NETLOOM_OUT_DIR
is still written.

The plugin normalizes payloads before replaying them so response-only metadata,
links, IDs, and similar API noise are not sent back as write input.

.SH DIFF WORKFLOW
The ClearPass plugin also supports read-only comparison between two named
profiles.

Preferred syntax:

.PP
.EX
netloom <module> <service> diff --from=SOURCE --to=TARGET [options]
.EE

Useful options include:

.TP
.BI --match-by= auto|name|id
Choose how source and target objects are matched.

.TP
.B --all
Compare the full selected collection on both profiles.

.TP
.BI --filter= JSON|FIELD:OP:VALUE
Compare the same filtered selection on both profiles.

.TP
.BI --fields= FIELD1,FIELD2
Restrict the comparison to named fields when supported by the selected action.

.TP
.BI --ignore-fields= FIELD1,FIELD2
Ignore named fields when comparing items.

.TP
.BI --out= FILE
Write the JSON diff report to an explicit file. If omitted, a generated
timestamped file under
.B NETLOOM_OUT_DIR
is still written.

.TP
.B --show-all
Disable console preview caps and print every listed diff item and changed
field.

.TP
.BI --max-items= N
Adjust the console preview cap for listed items and changed fields.

Broad selectors such as
.B --all
and
.B --filter
produce symmetric reports with
.BR same ,
.BR different ,
.BR only_in_source ,
and
.BR only_in_target
statuses. Narrow selectors such as
.B --id
and
.B --name
stay source-scoped and primarily answer whether the chosen source object matches
an object in the target profile.

.SH TROUBLESHOOTING
If a profile is not behaving as expected, start with:

.PP
.EX
netloom server show
.EE

If help or completion looks incomplete, refresh the cache:

.PP
.EX
netloom cache update
.EE

If a module or service seems to be missing for the current API client, inspect
the retained catalog:

.PP
.EX
netloom --catalog-view=full ?
.EE

.SH EXAMPLES
List endpoints:

.PP
.EX
netloom identities endpoint list --limit=10
.EE

Filter endpoints by name:

.PP
.EX
netloom identities endpoint list --filter=name:contains:guest
.EE

Get one network device by id:

.PP
.EX
netloom policyelements network-device get --id=1001
.EE

Copy matching network devices from one profile to another:

.PP
.EX
netloom policyelements network-device copy --from=dev --to=prod --all --dry-run
.EE

Compare roles between two profiles:

.PP
.EX
netloom policyelements role diff --from=lab --to=prod --all
.EE

Use action-specific help:

.PP
.EX
netloom policyelements network-device add ?
.EE

.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/defaults.env
ClearPass-wide defaults.

.TP
.B ~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/profiles/
Profile-specific connection settings.

.TP
.B ~/.config/netloom/plugins/clearpass/credentials/
Profile-specific credentials.

.TP
.B ~/.cache/netloom/
Default cache location used for discovered ClearPass API metadata.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR netloom (1)
